@{JCENTER}@{b}INTERNET CONNECTION PROBLEMS@{ub}
@{JLEFT}
To find out more information on Open Transport, Classic Networking and where to download relevant
files and software updates, click @{" here " LINK WWWinfo}.


@{b}What software do I need to connect to the internet? @{ub}

You have two choices, @{b}Classic Networking @{ub}(CN) or @{b}Open Transport @{ub}(OT). Both require certain Control
Panels and Extensions, as listed below:
@{b}CLASSIC NETWORKING...@{ub}
@{i}Control Panels: @{b}MacPPP: ConfigPPP @{" pic1 " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsConfigPPP1/main"} @{" pic2 " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsConfigPPP2/main"} @{" pic3 " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsConfigPPP3/main"} @{" pic4 " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsConfigPPP4/main"}@{ub}; or @{b}FreePPP @{" pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsFreePPP/main"}, MacTCP @{" pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsMacTCP/main"}.
@{ui}
@{b}OPEN TRANSPORT...@{ub}
@{i}Control Panels: Open Transport's @{b}PPP @{ub}@{" pic1 " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT4_CPsPPP1/main"} @{" pic2 " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT4_CPsPPP2/main"}, or @{b}FreePPP @{ub}@{" pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsFreePPP/main"};  @{b}Modem @{ub}@{" pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT4_CPsModem/main"}; and 
@{b}TCP/IP @{ub}@{" pic1 " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsTCP-IP/main"} @{" pic2 " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT4_CPsTCPIP_PPP/main"}.
@{ui}Open Transport v1.1 Extensions: @{b}Open Tpt AppleTalk Library, Open Tpt Internet Library, Open Transport 
Library, OpenTptAppleTalkLib, OpenTptInternetLib, OpenTransportLib.@{ub}


@{b}How do I get my modem "on-line"? @{ub}

You will find that @{b}Classic Networking @{ub}will work much better than Open Transport, @{i}but only on some
early versions of MacOS. For example, System 7.5x likes Classic Networking, while MacOS 7.6 to 8.1 
will tend to like using Open Transport better than CN. It all depends on what works smoothly for you! @{ui}
  Go to the PPP control panel (whatever it is you're using), and press the @{b}Connect @{ub}button. Now
you can use your internet browser, email or newsgroup program, that's it! Assuming of course that you
have setup the PPP control panel correctly, ie. you've supplied all the relevant data into it.
  Also make sure that the modem port is free, as in, the printer is not currently setup to use that
port at the moment - if it is, switch off the printer and plug in the modem and switch it on, then
retry connecting via the PPP control panel.


@{b}Where do I type in the settings for internet access? @{ub}

The two control panels you'll need to setup are the TCP/IP (Transport Control Protocol/Internet 
Protocol) and PPP (Point of Presence Protocol). All settings are saved in these two, however in OT,
it has a modem control panel, which stores information on the exact modem you're using.
  Please note that FreePPP will work with both CN and OT standards, except that it will be a little 
slower under OT, due to it not being fully OT optimised.
  Don't forget that in MacOS 8, it has a program that will take the hassle out of setting up internet
access, it is called @{b}Internet Setup Assistant,@{ub} and can be found in the Apple menu (or do
do a search via the Find command in the File menu, in the Finder). You still need to know information
about your Internet Provider and your modem etc, so that you can type it in the relevant boxes.


@{b}What type of files can I download from the internet? @{ub}

You have two choices; as an archive, or as "is" (unarchived and unencoded). There are many different 
types of archive that are pretty much standard on Macs: HQX, MacBinary, Zip, Compact Pro, Stuffit,
UUencoded and Disk Doubler being the most common.
  Some files can be transported as they are, because they do not have a resource fork, only a data
fork, therefore they cannot be damaged when transported onto different platforms. The type of files
I've managed to download from the net, onto my Amiga, and then onto my Mac, are: PDF (Adobe Acrobat)
files; SIT (Stuffit), GZIP, ZIP and LHA archive files; all types of image files (they really need a 3
character extension on the filename, for file type recognition). There may be others, but you're best 
sticking to these file types, and archiving any files your not sure about, before you upload them.
  See @{" File Problems " LINK Files} for further information on transferring files to/from a foreign platform,
and about archive types that are used on the Mac today.
@ENDNODE

