@{JCENTER}@{b}MISCELLANEOUS PROBLEMS
@{JLEFT}
@{i}Do Macs have Linux? @{ub}

Yep. You can find versions/information on Linux for Macintosh at:
@{b}http://www.linuxppc.com
http://www.yellowdoglinux.com
http://www.mklinux.apple.com @{ub}


@{b}Where can I download a free C/C++ compiler & documentation? @{ub}

You can download a free copy of @{b}Macintosh Programmer's Workshop @{ub}(MPW) from Apple's web site:
@{b}http://developer.apple.com/tools/mpw-tools/ @{ub}
It'll probably be easier to download the image files, as the whole thing comes to about 18mb.
  I don't know much about programming, but from what a newsgroup poster said... "MPW has a lot of 
flexibility, and you can do a tremendous amount of stuff once you get under the hood."
  The manual is in the Documentation folder, it is called @{b}Getting Started.@{ub}@{ui}  


@{b}Where can I find instructions for making AppleScript scripts? @{ub}

You can get a fair bit of information from Apple's extensive AppleScript web site, at;
@{b}http://www.apple.com/applescript/ @{ub}
  Or download a 2 megabyte PDF file;
@{b}http://developer.apple.com/techpubs/macos8/pdf/AppleScriptLanguageGuide.pdf @{ub}
Which gives the complete details on how Applescript works and what all the commands do etc.
  On a different note, you may like to use a different Script editor, other than Apple's own @{b}Script
Editor, @{ub}in which case check out @{b}Scripter @{ub}from Main Event Software (www.mainevent.com), or @{b}Script 
Debugger @{ub}from Late Night Software (www.latenightsw.com).


@{b}What if I don't have a high density floppy drive, can I use disk images? @{ub}

Yes you can use images, although you may find this to be inconvenient and only a short term solution,
so I suggest you save up for an external high density floppy drive for your Amiga.
  There are two popular Macintosh programs available at the moment, one is called @{b}Disk Copy v6.1 @{ub}from
Apple, and the other is @{b}Shrinkwrap v3.x @{ub}from Aladdin Systems - both are available from the internet.
Try these sites: @{b}www.shareware.com @{ub}(Shrinkwrap) and @{b}www.apple.com/support/ @{ub}(Disk Copy).
  These two programs can create, duplicate, lock/unlock and even mount any disk image onto the 
Desktop, this fools the Finder into believing they are real disks! They can also create disk images of
CD-ROM disks, and just about any other disk type for that matter, just make sure you have enough hard
disk space.


@{b}Where can I get Adobe Type Manager (ATM)? @{ub}

You can get ATM with Adobe Acrobat Reader v1 to v3.x. The latest version is v4.0.
  Certain Adobe software, such as Illustrator v6/v7, and Pagemaker v5 to v6 will have a copy of ATM
included on the CD-ROM or floppy disks. Or simply buy @{b}ATM Deluxe.@{ub}
  Note: ATM is a control panel. The Acrobat Reader installer usually installs it in it's Fonts folder.
Simply place it in the Control Panels folder to make it available for System wide use.


@{b}How do I know which Mac programs are 68k compatible? @{ub}

When you are about to buy any Mac software, make absolutely sure that it still supports 68k Macs.
Some of the top packages are now switching over to PowerPC code only, such as @{b}Photoshop 5, Norton
Utilities v4, Freehand 8, Illustrator 8 @{ub}and @{b}System 8.5.@{ub} I suggest you ring up the retailer or 
look in the software house's web site for confirmation of 68k compatibility.
  As for knowing which programs are PowerPC and which are 68k compatible, that's whole new ball game!
To find out if it is a PPC application, is simple, just launch it. If it is PowerPC only, it will
immediately display an error message, usually, error code -192, or an error message will be  displayed
telling you that this application is for PowerPC Macs only.
  Some Mac software is often (but not always) handed to the public as a 'Fat' application - this means
it has PowerPC and 68k code in the same file, so that it'll work on all Macs.
  As for seeing what type of code the program uses, externally, the only way to visually tell, is
either via it's filename, eg. "Quark Xpress 4.0 PPC", or via the About window/loading screen, these
may display information as to whether it is 100% 68k or Fat coded.


@{b}I'm having problems with Norton Utilities 3.2 and System 7.6/8.x, is it incompatible? @{ub}

Version 3.2 on it's own is not fully compatible with System 7.6x, you need to update it. Use the v3.24
updater, or use Norton v3.5, there is an updater on Symantec's web site: @{b}www.symantec.com.@{ub}
  Norton Utilities 3.5 will need to be updated to version 3.54, in order to be System 8 compliant.
Search for "updater" and this will give you a list of all updaters for all versions.
  If you intend to use the HFS+ filing system, then you must not use Norton Utils. (any version upto
v3.5 (all of which are 68k compatible)) on that HFS+ partition or disk, otherwise it'll destroy the 
disk's directory structure. However, TechTool Pro v2 will repair HFS+ disks, and it is 680x0 (CPU) 
compatible.


@{b}Where's the Norton Utilities 3.5 manual?@{ub}

Unfortunately Norton Utilities 3.5 does not have a physical manual, however you can download 
a PDF (Acrobat's Portable Document File) version of Norton Utilities 3.2 manual, from:
@{b}ftp://ftp.symantec.com/public/english_us_canada/products/norton_utilities/ver3.5_mac/updates/
num-manual.pdf.hqx @{ub}- this is 6mb, and covers everything you'll need to know for v3.5.


@{b}Is it possible make floppy based install disks to work on a hard disk?@{ub}

Yes, just make sure that you drag the entire disk onto the hard disk, so that all invisible files
are copied also. Note that, some install disks only work from floppy disks, but it is always a good
idea to make a backup copy of the disk, just in case it goes bad. This especially goes for anyone who
has their only copy of the System software on floppies - make sure you have a "master" backup copy of
the whole System disk set, you'll be glad you did, believe me!
