@NODE Detailed_Errors "Error Codes 1-31 in Detail"

@{JCENTER}@{b}POSITIVE ERROR CODES 1 TO 31: IN DETAIL@{ub}
@{JLEFT}

@{b}1 - Bus Error@{ub}
The computer tried to access memory that doesn't exist. You can get this error on almost any 
Macintosh. If one of these computers tried to access one or more bytes beyond the total number of 
bytes in RAM, you see a bus error.

@{b}2 - Address Error@{ub}
The Motorola 68000 microprocessor can access memory in increments of one byte (8 bits), one word 
(16 bits), or one long word (32 bits). The microprocessor can access a byte of information at an odd 
or even memory address. But it must access a word or long word at an even memory address. So, when 
the microprocessor attempts to read or write a word or long word at an odd address, you see this 
error. Since that's a 50/50 proposition when running random code, this one shows up quite often.

@{b}3 - Illegal Instruction@{ub}
If the computer tries to execute an instruction that isn't in its vocabulary, you see this error code.
It's less likely than error 02, but still very common.

@{b}4 - Zero Divide Error@{ub}
This error occurs if the CPU divides two numbers, and the divisor is zero.

@{b}5 - Range Check Error@{ub}
An instruction is used to check if a number is within a certain range, if not, this error is 
displayed.

@{b}6 - Overflow Error@{ub}
An overflow condition results if a generated number is too big for its allotted space.

@{b}7 - Privilege Violation@{ub}
The 68000 runs in Supervisor or User mode. The Macintosh should always be in Supervisor mode as some 
instructions can only be used in this mode, but sometimes it is placed in User mode. This error 
results if an Supervisor instruction was run in User mode.

@{b}8 - Trace Mode Error@{ub}
A programmer can use a runtime debugger while in Trace mode. This allows tracing through a program 
one instruction at a time. You see this error if a debugger isn't installed and the 68000 is 
accidentally placed in Trace mode.

@{b}9 & 10 - Line 1010 & 1111 Trap@{ub}
There are many routines in the Macintosh ROM that can be called by placing instructions in a program 
that aren't in the 68000's vocabulary. When the CPU encounters such an instruction, it looks it up 
in the instruction table. If it finds that there's no entry for the instruction, you see one of 
these errors.

@{b}11 - Miscellaneous Hardware Exception Error@{ub}
A Type 11 error is listed as a hardware exception error. However, Type 11 errors are more general 
in nature, and usually have nothing to do with hardware problems - it more likely a software 
instruction trying to do something that the hardware cannot do. You may see more Type 11 errors on 
a Power Macintosh computer because of problems with the software-based 68k emulation.

@{b}12 - Unimplemented Core Routine@{ub}
A programmer might set breakpoints in parts of a program to inspect for errors. If a debugger isn't 
installed when a breakpoint occurs, you see this error code.

@{b}13 - Uninstalled Interrupt@{ub}
The Macintosh uses an interrupt to identify when devices like keyboards and disk drives need service.
Routines must be available in memory to tell the computer how to service the device. If those 
routines aren't available, you see this error.

@{b}15 - Segment Loader Error@{ub}
The segment loader is responsible for loading a needed program allocated segment into RAM. If the 
segment loader can't do this, you'll see this error.

@{b}17-24 - Missing Packages 0-7@{ub}
If you get these errors, you probably have a damaged System file. Error codes 15, 16, 26, 27, 30, and
31 also come up when the System file is damaged.

@{b}25 - Memory Full Error@{ub}
You've run out of RAM!

@{b}26 - Bad Program Launch@{ub}
The application could not be executed.

@{b}28 - Stack Ran into Heap@{ub}
This is a memory related error, basically it was trying to use memory that is already in use.

@{b}27,30-31@{ub}
See Missing Packets.
@ENDNODE

