@NODE CPs "Contents / Useful MacOS Information / Control Panels"

@{JCENTER}@{b}THE STANDARD COMPONENTS OF A MAC'S SYSTEM FOLDER@{ub}

@{JLEFT}
I've listed most of the standard System components that'll be installed (from MacOS 7.53 to 7.6) and 
what they do exactly, these are; @{b}Control Panels, Extensions, Libraries, System Enablers @{ub}and loose
items in the @{b}System Folder.@{ub} Some of these extensions and control panels may not be available on an 
Amiga but they are usually installed anyway - I've highlighted these with a bold message.
  There are two excellent self viewing documents which explains every single System component in 
detail, and they're called @{b}Extension Overload @{ub}and @{b}InformINIT.@{ub} Both cover Systems 
7.x to 8.x, and include all of Apples's standard System files and most known third party 
extensions and control panels - both have very useful additional info concerning: Libraries,
Enablers and other types of files.

@{JCENTER}@{b}Select one of these buttons to go to the other categories: @{ub}
@{" Extensions " LINK Extensions} @{" Libraries " LINK Libs} @{" System Folder " LINK SystemFolder} @{" System Enablers " LINK SysEnable} @{" Menu " LINK Info}

@{b}STANDARD APPLE CONTROL PANELS @{ub}
@{JLEFT}
What is a control panel? A control panel is a small piece of software that allows you to customise 
certain settings that meet your needs. For example, you can change the pattern or colour of your
computer's desktop using the Desktop Patterns control panel.
  Depending on the type of computer you have and the System version you`re using, the contents of your
Control Panels folder may vary. You might also have control panels that were added by third-party 
applications. You can see a complete detailed list of all Apple control panels in the "Macintosh 
Guide" via the "?" menu, or press the Help key (only in System 7.5 or later).
 Here are some @{" odd control panels " LINK oddCPs} that the installer placed in your system, but may not need.


@{b}Appearance @{ub}(MacOS 8 only)
Controls how the MacOS 'looks', this is also where you can add 'themes' to the GUI. @{" Pic1 " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsAppearance1/main"} @{" Pic2 " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsAppearance2/main"}

@{b}Apple Menu Options@{ub}
Provides hierarchical sub-menus in the Apple Menu. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsAuto&Menus/main"}

@{b}AppleTalk@{ub}
You can specify AppleTalk settings (such as connection port and zone) for use with Apple's Open 
Transport networking. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsNtwrk+Appltk/main"}

@{b}At Ease Setup@{ub}
Allows you to start up your Mac in a simple, configurable launcher, which replaces the standard 
Finder.

@{B}ATM@{UB}
Makes your Type 1 fonts look sharp and clear at any point size, both on your screen and on paper.
Improves the output of QuickDraw printers, such as the ImageWriter and StyleWriter series. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsATM/main"}

@{b}ATM GX@{ub}
For displaying smooth QuickDrawGX fonts. Apple no longer supports QuickDrawGX features.

@{b}AutoRemounter @{ub}
Allows remounting of volumes after waking from sleep, on Powerbooks. It also works on desktop Macs,
to remount shared disks instead of using the AppleShare "mount on startup" option. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsAuto&Menus/main"}

@{b}Cache Switch @{ub}
For 68040/680LC40 Macs only. Allows you to turn off the 68040 processor caching for compatibility with
older applications. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPs040+Speech/main"}

@{B}Colour@{UB}
You can set the colour of highlighted text and window borders. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsColour&Sync/main"}

@{B}CloseView@{UB}
You can magnify your computer display for easier viewing.

@{B}ColourSync System Profile@{UB}
Part of the ColourSync system that provides consistent colour across various types of equipment 
(printers, scanners, monitors, and so on). In the control panel, you can view and select ColourSync 
profiles for the types of equipment you use. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsColour&Sync/main"}

@{B}Control Strip@{UB}
You can display or hide the Control Strip, and specify a font for Control Strip menus. With the 
Control Strip, you can control a variety of settings directly from your desktop, such as sound volume,
monitor resolution, file sharing, and so on. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsLanch+CtlStrp/main"}

@{B}Date & Time@{UB}
You can set the date, time, and time zone on your computer. You can also set how dates and times are 
displayed. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsDate+Map/main"}

@{B}Desktop Patterns@{UB}
You can change the pattern or colour of your computer's desktop. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsDktpPt+Keybd/main"}

@{b}Desktop Pictures @{ub}
This control panel replaces Desktop Pictures in MacOS 8.x. This time not only can you select a pattern
for the Desktop, but you can also place an image onto Desktop. @{" Pic1 " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsDesktopPic1/main"} @{" Pic2 " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsDesktopPic2/main"}

@{b}Easy Access@{ub}
Provides keyboard enhancements, and easier mouse input, and audio/visual feedback on keyboard entries
for people with disabilities.

@{b}Editor Setup@{UB}
You can specify which OpenDoc parts to use for different kinds of file formats. System 7.6-8.1 only.

@{b}Extensions Manager@{ub}
You can turn your computer's system extensions on or off. Extensions include items in the Extensions
folder, control panels, and other startup programs in the System Folder. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsExtMngr+EsyOpn/main"}

@{B}File Sharing Monitor @{UB}
When file sharing is turned on, this control panel displays a list of users who are connected to your
computer. @{b}Only available on networked Amigas.@{ub} @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsFileSharing/main"}

@{B}General Controls @{UB}
You can set various options, including desktop hiding, Launcher visibility at startup, folder 
protection to prevent folders and files from being deleted, insertion point blinking rate, menu 
selection blinking, and the default folder that appears in the Save dialogue box. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsGeneral/main"}

@{B}Keyboard @{UB}
You can set the repeat rate and delay before repeat for your keyboard. Also lets you switch keyboard
layouts. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsDktpPt+Keybd/main"}

@{B}Labels @{UB}
You can customize the colour and text of icon labels. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsViews+Labels/main"}

@{B}Launcher @{UB}
You can open the Launcher window, where you can easily find and open programs. You can add items to 
the Launcher by placing an alias to your favourite applications, files, or folders in the Launcher 
Items folder in the System Folder. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsLanch+CtlStrp/main"}

@{b}Mac OS Easy Open/Macintosh Easy Open @{ub}
Allows you to select the way a Mac or DOS/Windows file is translated/opened when you don't have the 
application that created it. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsExtMngr+EsyOpn/main"}

@{b}MacIPX @{ub}
Used with the MacIPX network extensions to provide support for the MacIPX network protocol.

@{b}MacPPP @{ub}
Is System 7.5x's PPP control panel for connecting the modem to the internet. This control panel can be
found on the System 7.53 or 7.6 CD, it is actually called Config PPP, and is relatively easy to set-up
despite the number of options screens available for you to fine tune. It also comes with a PPP system
extension, which you manually drop into the Extensions folder.
  MacPPP's main setup @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsConfigPPP1/main"}; the IPCP Options and Authentication windows @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsConfigPPP2/main"};
the Command Script window @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsConfigPPP3/main"}; the LCP Options @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsConfigPPP4/main"}.

@{b}MacTCP @{ub}
Used to configure and connect to TCP/IP-based networks, either locally or dial-up. Replaced by the 
TCP/IP control panel under Open Transport.

@{b}MacTCP DNR @{ub}
This file, which is loose in your system folder. DNR (Domain Name Resolver) contains part of the 
information needed by TCP/IP applications. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsMacTCP/main"}

@{B}Map @{UB}
You can locate popular cities around the world, and display longitude and latitude coordinates and 
local time. Lets you set the location of your computer. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsDate+Map/main"}

@{b}Memory @{ub}
Lets you control settings such as virtual memory, disk cache size, the Modern Memory Manager, RAM 
disks and 24-bit/32-bit addressing switch. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsMemory/main"}

@{i}@{b}Modem @{ub}(MacOS 8 only)
The Modem control panel allows you to use "Modem Scripts", or modem drivers. This allows MacOS to 
optimise performfance of the modem and allow for a much smoother operation when in use. The System
installer, installs drivers for most of the up-to-date modems for you, however if your particular 
model is not listed, then down load a Mac Modem Script from the manufacturer's web site, or look in 
the MacOS CD (quite a few are not installed). @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT4_CPsModem/main"}@{ui}

@{b}Monitors @{ub}
Allows you to configure your monitors; no. of colours/greys, resolution, main monitor on multiple
monitor systems for non-PCI Macs and the 7200 series PCI Macs. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsMonitor&Mouse/main"}

@{b}Monitors & Sound @{ub}(MacOS 8 only)
A combined control panel that replaces the separate Sound and Monitors control panels.
Monitor setup @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsMonitor&Sound1/main"}; sound setup @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsMonitor&Sound2/main"}; alerts setup @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsMonitor&Sound3/main"}.

@{B}Mouse @{UB}
You can set the tracking speed and double-click speed for your mouse. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsMonitor&Mouse/main"}

@{b}Network @{ub}
Used to choose the type of network in Systems 7.0-7.1x. Replaced by the AppleTalk control panel under
Open Transport. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsNtwrk+Appltk/main"}

@{B}Numbers @{UB}
You can control how numbers and currencies are displayed on your computer (for example, where decimal
points appear). @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsStrtDk+No+Txt/main"}

@{B}PC Exchange @{UB}
Allows your computer to read files from ProDOS and MS-DOS disks. You can specify the Mac OS 
application program used to open a DOS document. You can also use SyQuest and Bernoulli disks on your
desktop. @{" Pic1 " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsPCExchange/main"}

@{i}@{b}PPP @{ub}
Is part of the Open Transport PPP package (download from Apple). This allows you to use PPP through
Open Transport. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT4_CPsPPP1/main"} - shows PPP disconnected. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT4_CPsPPP2/main"} - shows PPP connected.@{ui}

@{B}QuickTime Settings @{UB}
This changes the preferences for QuickTime 2.5.You can set options for MIDI instruments, and set a CD
to play automatically when inserted. 

@{B}Sharing Setup @{UB}
You can set file sharing options and specify a network name for your computer. @{b}Only available on 
networked Amigas.@{ub} @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsSharingSetup/main"}

@{B}Sound @{UB}
You can set the alert sound and volume and specify a sound input and sound output source for your 
computer. On PowerPC-based computers with PCI slots, this control panel is replaced by the Monitors 
and Sound control panel.

@{B}Speech @{UB}
You can set options for hearing text read aloud by the computer. If you have Speakable Items software
and a PlainTalk-compatible microphone, you can set options for giving spoken commands to the computer.
Works on all Macintosh 660AV and 840AV computers. Also works on all computers with PowerPC 
microprocessors. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPs040+Speech/main"}

@{B}Startup Disk @{UB}
Select the disk you want to start up your computer (it must have a compatible System Folder on it).
@{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsStrtDk+No+Txt/main"}

@{B}TCP/IP @{UB}
@{i}You can specify TCP/IP settings for use with Apple's Open Transport and Ethernet. @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT3_CPsTCP-IP/main"}
TCP/IP can also be used to setup your modem's PPP/ISP details: @{" Pic " LINK "MacGuideIV_Pics/MT4_CPsTCPIP_PPP/main"}
There is one drawback to the Mac's TCP/IP control panel, it cannot connect to an Ethernet network, and 
connect to the internet via PPP at the same time, unless you're connected via Ethernet to internet 
router system.@{ui} 

@{B}Text @{UB}
