@TITLE "Contents / Useful MacOS Information / Control Panels / Odd Control Panels"

@{JCENTER}@{b}OTHER CONTROL PANELS
@{JLEFT}
Some of these Control Panels (CP) may have been installed with the "standard set" of control panels.
99% of these will not apply to you, or simply won't work (it'll give an error message if you try to
double click on an incompatible CP), so you can safely bin most of them.

AppleCD Speed Switch @{ub}
From System 7.1. Allows you to switch between "standard" or "faster" speed. It is integrated into 
CD Software 5.0.

@{b}AppleShareSetup @{ub}
Allows you to change many of the AppleShare parameters.

@{b}AppleTalk Options@{ub}
Part of the Open Transport package, but not installed automatically. It allows a user to suppress
unwanted router-related alerts.

@{b}AppleVision Setup @{ub}
For PCI Macs; after upgrading to System 7.5.3, this Control Panel should be eliminated. All of its 
functionality will be incorporated into the Monitors & Sound control panel.

@{b}Auto Power On/Of @{ub}
Allows your Mac to automatically shut down after a specified idle time, reboot after a power failure,
and/or start up or shut down at a certain times.

@{b}Button Disabler @{ub}
Allows you to disable the volume, brightness etc. buttons on the front of certain computer models, 
ie. the LC/Performa 500 series Macs.

@{b}CPU Energy Saver @{ub}
Allows you to turn your Mac off at a specific time or after a specified amount of idle time.

@{b}DOS Compatibility Software Update / PC Setup @{ub}
Used by Macs with the DOS Compatibility Card.

@{b}Energy Saver @{ub}
Allows you to put your external monitor into sleep mode after a specified idle time. It only works 
with Macs that have the built-in video, it also requires an Energy Star compliant monitor.
@{b}Compatible with PCI based PowerMacs only.@{ub}

@{b}LaserWriter Bridge @{ub}
Open Transport-compatible version of LaserWriter Bridge and LocalTalk Bridge. Allows you to use 
LocalTalk printers and access LocalTalk networked Macs over an Ethernet or TokenRing network.

@{b}LocalTalk Bridge @{ub}
Allows you to bridge Ethernet and LocalTalk networks.

@{b}MODE32 @{ub}
Under System 7, gives the Mac II, IIx, IIcx, or SE/30 the ability to run in 32-bit addressing mode.
With 32-bit addressing on, your Mac can take advantage of more than 8MB of RAM. Under System 7.5, a
new version of MODE32 was released. You MUST use MODE32 7.5 if you are running System 7.5.
@{b}This CP is not necessary for Mac emulation on Amigas - 32 bit addressing is guaranteed.@{ub}

@{b}Network Time @{ub}
If you are on a network with a Time Server, this control panel checks the server and synchronizes 
your Mac's clock.

@{b}Pasword Security @{ub}
Used on portable Macs only, and will not work in emulation anyway. Allows you to lock-out the Mac's
hard disk, so that thieves cannot use the computer.

@{b}PC Setup @{ub}
Used by Macs with the 610 PC and DOS Compatibility Cards, and is replaced by the DOS Compatibility 
Software Update 1.5.

@{b}Performa @{ub}
Included with Performa models running System 7.1P. Provides functionality similar to the General 
Controls control panel.

@{b}Power Macintosh Card + 601 Processor Upgrade @{ub}
Allows the use of a PowerPC accelerator on a real Mac. Cannot work in emulation.

@{b}ScriptSwitcher @{ub}
Provides a quick way to automatically switch the primary script system resources in your System 
software..

@{b}Serial Switch @{UB}
Provides compatibility for some applications that use the printer or modem port. You can set the 
serial port option to Faster or More Compatible. @{b}Works on Macintosh IIfx and Macintosh Quadra 950 
computers only.@{ub}

@{b}Token Ring @{ub}
Under Open Transport, works with the AppleTalk control panel to allow access to a Token Ring network.

@{b}Trackpad @{ub}
Used on portable Macs only. It controls the trackball, for speed control and button use.
@ENDNODE

