@NODE Extensions "Contents / Useful MacOS Information / Extensions"

@{JCENTER}@{b}STANDARD APPLE EXTENSIONS@{ub}
@{JLEFT}
What is an Extension? An Extension is a small file that changes how your computer operates. Unlike 
a control panel, you typically do not have any direct interaction with an Extension. An Extension 
makes the appropriate changes when you start your computer and remains active until you shutdown your
computer. 
  Depending on the type of computer you have, the contents of your Extensions folder may vary. You 
might also have extensions that were added by third-party applications.
  To disable an Extension, simply take it out of the Extension Folder and put it in a folder called
"Extensions (disabled)", this can be placed in the System Folder, don't worry, no Extension will be
loaded from this particular folder. You can also use the Extension Manager control panel to do the
same thing.
  Other types of extensions are actually Libraries, these are often used by many applications or
system components. It is usually a good idea not to turn off libraries, otherwise it may cause some
programs not to load up. Some of the more common ones are listed in the Libraries link below.
 Here are some @{" odd extensions " LINK oddEXTs} that the installer placed in your system that you may not need.

@{JCENTER}@{b}Select one of these buttons to go to the other categories: @{ub}
@{" Control Panels " LINK CPs} @{" Libraries " LINK Libs} @{" System Folder " LINK SystemFolder} @{" System Enablers " LINK SysEnable} @{" Menu " LINK Info}
@{JLEFT}

@{B}EM Extension @{UB}
Works with the Extensions Manager control panel, which lets you specify which extensions are turned 
on when you start your computer.

@{B}About Apple Guide @{UB}
Provides information about how to use Apple's on-screen help system.

@{b}ADSP @{ub}
AppleTalk Data Stream Protocol, provides networking protocol under pre-7.0 systems. More specifically,
it provided data flow and full duplex data delivery over a network. However, in order for the benefits
to be realized, both Macs had to be running this extension.

@{b}AppleCD Audio Player Guide @{ub}
Provides step-by-step instructions for using the AppleCD Audio Player.

@{B}Apple CD-ROM @{UB}
Enables your computer to use an Apple CD-ROM drive. 

@{B}Apple Color SW Pro CMM @{UB}
Contains colour-matching information used by ColorSync 2.0 to maintain consistent colour between 
documents.

@{B}AppleGuide @{UB}
Enables your computer to use Apple's on-screen help system. You can access Macintosh Guide from the ?
menu (the help menu is on the right hand side of the menu-bar), whilst in the Finder. This feature can
only be found in Systems 7.5 to 8.1.

@{b}APPLEGUIDE ADDITIONS: 
-AppleVision Guide Additions 
-AV Guide Additions 
-Energy Saver Guide Additions 
-Monitors & Sound Guide Additions 
-Network Guide Additions 
-Open Transport Guide Additions 
-Speech Guide Additions 
-Video Guide Additions @{ub}
Adds step-by-step instructions for using features specific to a program, MacOS, or control panel.

@{b}Apple Multimedia Tuner @{ub}
Enhances QuickTime 2.0 and Sound Manager 3.0. Once you upgrade to QuickTime 2.1 and Sound Manager 3.1,
or System 7.5.3/Update 2.0, this is no longer necessary.

@{B}Apple Photo Access @{UB}
Part of the CD-ROM software, and is needed for viewing Kodak PhotoCDs.

@{B}AppleScript @{UB}
Enables automation of repetitive tasks in applications that support it. Some applications, such as 
Apple on-screen help, require AppleScript to work. 

@{B}AppleShare @{UB}
Gives you access to shared disks on the network. Systems 7.6 through to 8.1 uses a later version of
AppleShare that is incompatible with ShapeShifter up to v3.10.

@{B}Audio CD Access @{UB}
Lets you play audio CDs on your internal or external CD-ROM drive. Requires the AppleCD Audio Player
or equivalent application to control the audio CD.

@{B}Clipping Extension @{UB}
Lets you use the drag-and-drop feature to create clipping files on your desktop.

@{B}Color Picker @{UB}
Creates a standard colour selection interface for all applications.

@{B}Color SW 2000 Series CMM @{UB}
Colour-matching information used by ColorSync to maintain consistent colour between documents printed 
on a Color StyleWriter 2000 series printer and other colour devices.

@{B}ColorSync @{UB}
Matches colours on your display with the closest matching colours on your printers, scanners, and other
devices.

@{b}Desktop Printer Extension @{ub}/@{b} Desktop Printer Spooler @{ub}/@{b} Desktop PrintMonitor@{ub}
All three of these files are necessary for the desktop printing feature to work. (With desktop 
printing, you can print documents by dragging their icons to printer icons.) 

@{b}Dragging Enabler @{ub}/@{b} Drag Enabler@{ub}
Provides Drag Manager support under System 7.0 and 7.1. When used with the Macintosh Drag and Drop 
extension, provides inter-application drag and drop support under System 7.1. Integrated into the 
Finder under System 7 Pro and later.

@{b}Energy Saver Extension @{ub}
Used in conjunction with the Energy Saver Control Panel. Sends the Mac to sleep.

@{B}Ethertalk Phase 2 @{UB}
Lets you connect your computer to an Ethernet network.

@{B}File Sharing Extension @{UB}
Enables your computer to share files and folders with other computers on your network. 

@{B}Find File Extension @{UB}
Lets you search for files and view the results in a single window. If you turn off this extension and
choose Find from the File menu, you'll get the System 7.1 Find dialogue box instead of Find File.

@{B}Finder Help @{UB}
Provides Balloon Help support for the Finder.

@{B}Finder Scripting Extension @{UB}
Allows you to use AppleScript to automate tasks in the Finder.

@{B}Foreign File Access@{UB}
Enables your computer to work with CD-ROM discs whose contents don't use the standard Mac OS file 
system (for example, ISO 9660 or High Sierra formats).

@{B}Global Guide Files folder @{UB}
Contains files used by the on-screen help system. Some of these files may be used to provide help more
than one application. 

@{B}High Sierra File Access @{UB}
Part of the CD-ROM software that lets you view CDs with High Sierra file systems.

@{b}Installer Cleanup @{ub}
This is put in the System Folder after a OS is installed. All it does is to make sure that the 
installation process was successful and that everything was installed in the proper place. You must 
allow it to load on the next restart so that it can take care of any files that were left behind after
the installation. It should then disappear.

@{B}ISO 9660 File Access @{UB}
Part of the CD-ROM software that lets you view CDs with ISO 9660 file systems.

@{B}LaserWriter 8 @{UB}
(version 8.x) A PostScript level II print driver that enables your computer to print documents on a 
PostScript printer connected to an AppleTalk network. 

@{B}Mac OS Guide @{UB}
Contains step-by-step instructions for working in the Finder. You access Mac OS Guide from the Guide 
(question mark) menu when the Finder is active. 

@{B}MacinTalk 3 @{UB}
Lets your computer read text documents in human-like voices. 

@{b}MacinTalk Pro @{ub}
Lets your computer read text documents in human-like voices. Older computers (with 68030 or 020 
processors) should use MacinTalk 3 instead.

@{b}Macintosh Drag @{ub}/@{b} Drag&Drop Extension@{ub}
Provides Drag and Drop support under Systems 7.0.x and 7.1.x. These two files are still installed by 
numerous software packages, such as Now Utilities and ccMail, for universal compatibility, but are not
needed under System 7.5 and later.

@{b}MacIPX AppleTalk @{ub}/@{b} MacIPX TCP/IP @{ub}/@{b} MacIPX Token Rink@{ub}
These are network drivers which support the MacIPX protocol over the respective network type 
(ie. AppleTalk, TCP/IP or Token Ring).

@{b}MacTCP Token Ring Extension @{ub}
Allows you to use the TCP/IP protocol over a Token Ring network.

@{b}Mailbox Extension @{ub}
Supports your PowerTalk mailbox. Enables the Mailbox icon to appear on your desktop.

@{B}My Speech Macros @{UB}
Supports the Speech Macro Editor.

@{B}Network Extension @{UB}
Lets you set Personal File Sharing from the Finder.

@{B}Printer Descriptions @{UB}
This folder contains printer description files (PDFs) for most of Apple's laser printers.

@{b}Printer Driver Extensions @{ub}
These are extensions which allow access/connection to various types of networks, services, printers,
etc. using the Chooser. They do not take up any RAM when the System has booted-up. Most of these 
(99.9%) can be deleted out of the Extensions folder, it is highly likely you won't have any of these
printers.
